In [[number theory]], a '''sublime number''' is a positive [[integer]] which has a [[perfect number]] of positive [[Factorization|factors ]] (including itself), and whose positive factors add up to another perfect number.<ref>MathPages article, [http://www.mathpages.com/home/kmath202/kmath202.htm "Sublime Numbers"].</ref>

The number [[12 (number)|12]], for example, is a sublime number.  It has a perfect number of positive factors ([[6 (number)|6]]): 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, and 12, and the sum of these is again a perfect number: 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 6 + 12 = [[28 (number)|28]].

There are only two known sublime numbers, 12 and (2<sup>126</sup>)(2<sup>61</sup> − 1)(2<sup>31</sup> − 1)(2<sup>19</sup> − 1)(2<sup>7</sup> − 1)(2<sup>5</sup> − 1)(2<sup>3</sup> − 1)  {{OEIS|id=A081357}}.<ref>[[Clifford A. Pickover]], ''Wonders of Numbers, Adventures in Mathematics, Mind and Meaning'' New York: Oxford University Press (2003): 215</ref> The second of these has 76 decimal digits:
:6086555670238378989670371734243169622657830773351885970528324860512791691264.

