The primes for ''n''≥234760 were found by the [[distributed computing]] project '''321 search'''.<ref>[http://www.mersenneforum.org/321search/The%20status%20of%20the%20search.html]</ref> The largest of these, 3·2<sup>11895718</sup>−1, has 3580969 digits and was found in June 2015.

In 2008, [[Primegrid]] took over the search for Thabit primes.<ref>[http://primes.utm.edu/bios/page.php?id=479]</ref> It is still searching and has already found all currently known Thabit primes with n ≥ 4235414.<ref>[http://primes.utm.edu/primes/lists/short.txt]</ref> It is also searching for primes of the form 3·2<sup>''n''</sup>+1, such primes are called '''Thabit primes of the second kind''' or '''321 primes of the second kind'''.

